USD warrants have retraced to their starting levels for 2025 after legal setbacks, but still carry meaningful upside if courts rule in favour of plaintiffs, with timing of resolution the main obstacle. EUR warrants offer greater certainty but more limited upside, and still depend on Argentina paying.
The non- legalistic summary version of the Argentina GDP warrant outlook (see inside for the legal details):

- For the EUR GDP warrant, Argentina has run out of legal options and owes a payment of 7.9 points. So far, there is no sign of this being made. Once the election is behind us and if markets start to see Argentina regaining bond market access, the likelihood of a full payment should rise. In the meantime, plaintiffs are pursuing US-based assets to enforce their claims. With markets already pricing in a high chance that the 2013 payment will be made, the real upside lies in payments from 2014 onwards – though that hinges on a new GDP methodology being approved by the UK courts.

- For the USD GDP warrant, in 2025 Argentina has so far come out ahead, winning one case related to the 2013 payment year. Plaintiffs are expected to relaunch another case on 2013 while also pressing a third case covering 2014 onwards. The main source of potential upside remains the 2013 payment year, helped by the UK court ruling. If the US courts side with plaintiffs, that payment could be worth up to 15 points including judgement interest. This is not currently reflected in prices, with the warrant trading around 3. The hurdles are twofold: first, whether the US courts dismiss the case, and second, how long it would take for a ruling in the plaintiffs' favour. Additional upside could come from 2014 onwards, but – as with the EUR warrant – that depends on US'stours agreeing to a new GDP methodology.

Since our update in February (see Argentina Sovereign Credit Strategy & Economics: Warrants Back in Vogue, February 4, 2025) there have been a few moving parts on both the EUR and USD GDP warrant sides. We summarise the key events below and also attempt to show a broader overview in Appendix: Legal Overview.

The main focus is still on the (potential future) negotiations: As expanded on in our February 4 note, there is a final unappealable judgement on the EUR GDP warrants, which means that the next step is for Argentina to settle the judgement by making the full payment. While the latest IMF review noted that negotiations were ongoing between the plaintiffs and Argentina, the plaintiffs on August 12 published a statement that "no discussions are taking place".

Letter of credit drawn on to reduce the total claim: As part of being allowed to go ahead with the appeal, Argentina had to deposit funds into escrow, or provide a letter of credit, worth €313 million. Following all the appeal routes being exhausted and the judgement being final, this was subsequently made available to plaintiffs this year. €149 million was used to pay down the post- judgement interest up to January 28, 2025, another €111 million for the actual 2013 payment and the remainder for smaller items. In total, €279 million was paid to all holders, equivalent to around 1.47 warrant points.

Post this payment as of January 29, 2025, it left the total claim to all holders at €1.457 billion. As of April 1, 2025, this had increased to €1.468 billion given that the claim will again accrue post- judgement interest at Euribor+2%. As a share of the outstanding, this is 7.75 points. Today, we estimate that the claim is worth around 7.87 points.

Recognition and enforcement of the final judgement in the US: The final update is that on June 23 the plaintiffs filed to enforce their foreign money judgment (the €1.5 billion UK ruling) against the Republic of Argentina in the US District Court for the District of Columbia. The aim is presumably to increase the plaintiffs' leverage by opening up the possibility of pursuing Argentina's assets located in the US. Historically, it appears that uncontested cases take 3- 6 months before the judgement is entered recognising the foreign award.

At some point the GDP data from 2014 onwards will likely feature again: As part of the 2023 ruling, the UK courts ordered Argentina to calculate GDP for all years under the 1993 base year (Real_ GDP_Actual_1993). Argentina has done this but, as reviewed last time, it is inconsistent with what the same UK court agreed was a correct GDP number for 2013. So, presumably plaintiffs will be returning to courts at some point making this argument, potentially also suggesting what a continued 1993 GDP series could look like. That said, unlike for 2013 which had the EMAE reading for 4Q13 under the 1993 base year, this doesn't exist for the period from 2014 onwards, making it more challenging to derive alternative GDP numbers.
On the USGDP warrant
The US GDP warrant is more complicated as there are three ongoing cases:

US2019 (1:19- cv- 00351) - initial complaint brought in 2019 for 2013 reference year only (on behalf of plaintiff only). Latest status: Plaintiffs lost appeal in July 2025. US2023 (1:23- cv- 10838) - complaint brought in 2023 for 2014 reference year and beyond (on behalf of all holders). Latest status: Awaiting court ruling on Argentina's motion to dismiss. US2024 (1:24- cv- 07247) - back- up complaint to 2019 in case US2019 is dismissed by the courts. For 2013 reference year only (on behalf of all holders). Latest status: Was "paused" pending appeal in US2019 case; will presumably be restarted.

So far 2025 has been a setback for plaintiffs - adding time to eventual resolution: July 2025 saw plaintiffs lose their appeal against the US2019 case being dismissed due to the suit itself being barred by a "no- action clause". While it's possible that plaintiffs file a motion for reconsideration, our guess is that this now moves the timeline onto the US2024 case instead.

So far US2024 had been put on hold in February 2025 pending the outcome of US2019. The US2024 complaint also covers only the 2013 reference year but now files the complaint on behalf of all holders, potentially satisfying the no- action clause. Argentina's argument was subsequently that additional plaintiffs cannot be added due to being beyond the prescription deadline of December 15, 2019 (five years after 2013 reference year payment date of December 15, 2014) or the six- year NY statute of limitations that would have expired on December 15, 2020.

The NY district court will thus need to decide whether to dismiss the US2024 case. As a reminder, the initial March 2024 ruling on US2019 did not end up ruling on the underlying merits of the 2013 payments, simply dismissing it due to the no- action clause.

Notably, the 2013 payment depends on the US2024 case being successful: Coming back to the five- year prescription clause or six- year statute of limitations, it's worth noting that only the US2019 and potentially US2024 lawsuits can include the 2013 reference year where payment was due on December 15, 2014. This is important as 2013 is by far the easier year to argue for given that the UK courts have already issued a final judgement on how the GDP and resulting warrant payment should be calculated for 2013, meaning that it can in theory easily be followed by US courts.

The potential payments from 2014 onwards depend on US2023 being successful, which could be more difficult on the GDP calculations: The US2023 complaint covers all years from 2014 yet, given that it was filed in December 2023, it may be that the six- year statute of limitations (or five- year prescription clause) will only include payments due from 2017 onwards (or 2018), meaning reference years 2016 (or 2017).
The two key areas of uncertainty: To simplify the dispute, we can think of two areas, only one of which has been settled by the UK courts.

- The contractual interpretation settled by UK courts: Argentina and plaintiffs differed on how to interpret several important terms on the GDP warrant, yet the UK courts ruled in plaintiffs' favour on all. Our prior note described some of these in more detail yet it means that the adjustment ratio is calculated annually with both 1993 and 2004 base year data available and also that the annual growth benchmark will vary accordingly, instead of being fixed at 3%. While perhaps obvious, it's worth noting that the UK court ruling does not automatically apply to US courts, but it does increase the likelihood that the US courts make the same interpretation.

- The GDP numbers are more challenging and not yet settled: The UK court ordered Argentina to publish GDP data for all years from 2013 onwards under the 1993 base year. It has done this but, as noted in our prior publication, this may be questioned by plaintiffs in the UK, just as the US plaintiffs have already done.

How can a new GDP series under the 1993 base year look: We see three potential outcomes for the revised 1993 GDP data, with the first two outlined in more detailed in our prior note. There is then a fourth scenario which uses the official GDP data as currently published only up to 2012.

1. Base 1 – original GDP data only: While UK courts are not using this scenario, US courts have not yet made any final rulings, meaning that this is still officially what Argentina uses to calculate payments on the USD GDP warrant.

2. Base 2 – resumed 1993 data mandated by UK courts: This is what has been published by Argentina following the court order, which now goes up to 2023 and will presumably soon be updated for 2024 as well.

3. Base 3 – resumed 1993 data mandated by UK courts adjusted for 2013: This series shows the impact of adjusting the initial level of the resumed Real_GDP_Actual_1993 to that of the court-accepted 2013 value and then using the year-on-year growth rates as presented by Argentina in the same resumed GDP series.

4. Base 4 – custom series using basis between overlap years: This builds on the US'2023 complaint where plaintiffs note that Real_GDP_Actual_1993 tended to grow at a faster pace than Real_GDP_Actual_2004 in the years where both series were available. To put numbers to it, Real_GDP_Actual_1993 grew a cumulative 23pp GDP more than Real_GDP_Actual_2004 in 2004-12, or 1.84% higher on an annual basis. This contrasts to the new data published by Argentina in 2013-23 where the cumulative differential is only 1pp. A custom series could thus look to adjust for this basis. A simple approach would just apply the annual average basis of 1.84% yet there are likely more advanced approaches that would be more acceptable to courts. After all, given different weights and price levels, the series should differ. However, as an example we use this as a gauge of the potential upside. A caveat here, as also noted earlier, is that the courts may find it more difficult, or take longer, to agree to new GDP numbers given that it's not as simple as just using the EMAE series already published by Argentina.

Source: Haver Analytics, INDEC, legal filings in cases, Morgan Stanley Research calculations

These GDP scenarios are then combined with the potential legal outcomes: We show the complete potential payment schedules in Appendix: Potential Payments for each of these four scenarios. They summarise as follows for the USD warrant (Exhibit 2). Note these are all the historical payments due, not adjusting for pre/post- judgement interest.
Exhibit 2: Payments for the USD warrant under the different GDP scenarios (historical payment, not adjusted for interest)
Source: Haver Analytics, INDEC, legal filings in cases, Morgan Stanley Research calculations

- US'2019/US'2024: If using the original data released by Argentina (base 1) there is no payout. For all other scenarios we assume that the US courts will follow UK courts and use the UK court-determined 2013 GDP. This leaves a payment of 7.6 points. Adding on the pre-judgement interest rate of 9%, the payment due today would take it to around 14.8 points. Note that only in the US'2024 lawsuit would this payment be due to all holders, as opposed to the plaintiffs only in US'2019. 
- US 2023: Under most GDP calculations (base 1, 2 and 3) there are no payouts due to not satisfying the level conditions. Under base 4 there would be, as the level condition is now satisfied (as Real_GDP_Actual_1993 is increased materially). With potential payouts for 2017, 2021 and 2022, it would amount to 16 points at the time of payment, and 22 once adding pre-judgement interest. Note that as explained above we do not include the payment from 2015 due to it likely being beyond the statute of limitations and prescription periods.

2024 not seeing any payment: 2024 saw GDP growth of \(- 1.3\% Y\) (Real_GDP_Actual_2004) and, while much better than markets anticipated at the start of the year, this still does not come close to meeting the growth criterion (under all plausible Real_GDP_Actual_1993 series).

2025 and beyond could hold value yet both would come from bull case scenarios: For 2025, our economist currently forecasts growth of \(4.6\% Y,\) which is in line with the Bloomberg consensus. This would trigger the growth condition so the question would be the level condition. The extremes are base 2 (UK court- mandated data published by Argentina which would never see any payouts) and base 4 (custom data that would see all years comfortably meet the level condition (Exhibit 5)). Under base 3, a bullish growth scenario of \(5\% Y\) annually would see the level condition met by 2029 although payouts would be small given the small excess GDP. Under our economists' base case for growth, it would not cross the base level and thus not trigger at all.

In other words, future value largely comes from either: 1) A complete change in what US courts deem realistic GDP which results in a path much more in line with the US plaintiffs' proposal; or 2) Very high growth of around \(5\% Y\) annually from here.
Exhibit 5: Mapping future growth paths against the potential Real_GDP_Base_2004 scenarios
Source: Haver Analytics, INDEC, legal filings in cases, Morgan Stanley Research forecasts

Bonds the more straightforward way to play Argentina fixed income: Our prior note said that "Argentina's FX bonds and CDS are the most straightforward way to play the significant macro improvement ongoing in Argentina at the sovereign level" but also that we saw "potential upside for both warrants, but catalysts and timing are key".

Since then, the USD bonds have outperformed in total return terms, with the USD warrants at the lower end of ranges. But we still think that this preference holds today, i.e., bonds over warrants. For bonds, our base case remains that by the end of the year they price market access levels, which means yields just below \(10\%\) . It's just a matter of gauging the right entry point given the recent volatility before changing our view to a like stance.

- The straightforward upside comes from a judgement in favour of the plaintiffs in US'2024 covering the 2013 payment which could be worth nearly 15 points. Other than the difficulty in assessing the probability of this happening, although the positive UK court ruling helps, the uncertainty is the time it will take. US'2019 eventually took five years to get to a ruling, yet we suspect that it would be quicker the second time around.- Additional potential upside then comes from the US'2023 suit, yet this is perhaps more uncertain due to the need for the US courts to agree to a GDP methodology favouring plaintiffs from 2014 onwards.- All in, the USD warrant is thus a cheap option, in our view, especially given that it's currently trading at the lower end of recent ranges around 3. Progress on any of the current lawsuits should see upside moves.

- At a price of 9 it should include a high probability of payment of the 7.9 points due to 2013 with the remainder of the value coming from the potential for the years from 2014 seeing a payout, including future years.- Without a court-accepted GDP, it's hard to assess the potential value. If a GDP methodology similar to the one proposed in the US case is used, there is significant upside, yet that is not a certainty as different approaches may be used.
